<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Home Gardeners Should Actually Buy</h2>

  <p>
    For most home grafting setups, buy a small assortment covering the useful middle of the 2.0 to 4.5 mm range rather than betting everything on one size. That gives you room for natural seedling variation and makes it easier to match the clip to the actual stem diameter at graft time.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use smaller sizes for very young, fine stems and larger sizes only when seedlings are clearly thicker. In most cases, fit matters more than having a huge assortment or the most specialized clip style.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best clip size is the one that fits the stem you have today, not the one you expected last week.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The 2.0 to 4.5 mm range covers most of what home gardeners need for vegetable grafting, but the useful size depends on stem thickness at the graft point.
  </p>

  <p>
    Smaller clips suit early, fine-stemmed seedlings, while larger clips help when stems are thicker or more variable. For most home gardeners, a modest assortment centered around the middle of the range is the most practical choice.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Do not buy the whole range blindly. Buy enough range to match real seedlings well.
  </p>
</section>